<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" ?>
<subsection xml:id="posthoc-holm">
    <title>Holm corrections</title>

    <p>Although the Bonferroni correction is the simplest adjustment out there, it's not usually the best one to use. One method that is often used instead is the <em>Holm correction</em> (<xref ref="biblio-Holm1979">Holm, 1979</xref>). The idea behind the Holm correction is to pretend that you're doing the tests sequentially; starting with the smallest (raw) <m><![CDATA[p]]></m>-value and moving onto the largest one. For the <m><![CDATA[j]]></m>-th largest of the <m><![CDATA[p]]></m>-values, the adjustment is <em>either</em></p>
    <me><![CDATA[p^\prime_j = j \times p_j]]></me>
    <p>(i.e., the biggest <m><![CDATA[p]]></m>-value remains unchanged, the second biggest <m><![CDATA[p]]></m>-value is doubled, the third biggest <m><![CDATA[p]]></m>-value is tripled, and so on), <em>or</em></p>
    <me><![CDATA[p^\prime_j = p^\prime_{j+1}]]></me>
    <p>whichever one is <em>larger</em>. This might sound a little confusing, so let's go through it a little more slowly. Here's what the Holm correction does. First, you sort all of your <m><![CDATA[p]]></m>-values in order, from smallest to largest. For the smallest <m><![CDATA[p]]></m>-value all you do is multiply it by <m><![CDATA[m]]></m>, and you're done. However, for all the other ones it's a two-stage process. For instance, when you move to the second smallest <m><![CDATA[p]]></m> value, you first multiply it by <m><![CDATA[m-1]]></m>. If this produces a number that is bigger than the adjusted <m><![CDATA[p]]></m>-value that you got last time, then you keep it. But if it's smaller than the last one, then you copy the last <m><![CDATA[p]]></m>-value. To illustrate how this works, consider the table below, which shows the calculations of a Holm correction for a collection of five <m><![CDATA[p]]></m>-values:</p>
        <table xml:id="table-chanova-35">
      <tabular halign="center">
        <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
          <cell halign="left">raw <m>p</m></cell>
          <cell>rank <m>j</m></cell>
          <cell><m>p \times j</m></cell>
          <cell>Holm <m>p</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell halign="left">.001</cell>
          <cell>5</cell>
          <cell>.005</cell>
          <cell>.005</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell halign="left">.005</cell>
          <cell>4</cell>
          <cell>.020</cell>
          <cell>.020</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell halign="left">.019</cell>
          <cell>3</cell>
          <cell>.057</cell>
          <cell>.057</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell halign="left">.022</cell>
          <cell>2</cell>
          <cell>.044</cell>
          <cell>.057</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell halign="left">.103</cell>
          <cell>1</cell>
          <cell>.103</cell>
          <cell>.103</cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <p>Hopefully that makes things clear.</p>
    <p>Although it's a little harder to calculate, the Holm correction has some very nice properties: it's more powerful than Bonferroni (i.e., it has a lower Type II error rate), but -- counterintuitive as it might seem -- it has the <em>same</em> Type I error rate. As a consequence, in practice there's never any reason to use the simpler Bonferroni correction, since it is always outperformed by the slightly more elaborate Holm correction. Because of this, the Holm correction is the default one used by <c>pairwise.t.test()</c> and <c>posthocPairwiseT()</c>. To run the Holm correction in R, you could specify <c>p.adjust.method = "Holm"</c> if you wanted to, but since it's the default you can just to do this:</p>
    <remark>
      <title>R Code</title>
    <program language="r">
  <input><![CDATA[
posthocPairwiseT( my.anova )]]></input>
</program>
    <console>
      <output><![CDATA[
## 
##  Pairwise comparisons using t tests with pooled SD 
## 
## data:  mood.gain and drug 
## 
##          placebo anxifree
## anxifree 0.1502  -       
## joyzepam 9.1e-05 0.0011  
## 
## P value adjustment method: holm
]]></output>
    </console>
    </remark>
    <p>As you can see, the biggest <m><![CDATA[p]]></m>-value (corresponding to the comparison between Anxifree and the placebo) is unaltered: at a value of <m><![CDATA[.15]]></m>, it is exactly the same as the value we got originally when we applied no correction at all. In contrast, the smallest <m><![CDATA[p]]></m>-value (Joyzepam versus placebo) has been multiplied by three.</p>
</subsection>
